title: For Sale/Trade:  Remington 700P KRG x-Ray stock
postcontent:
Custom Remington 700P
This rifle has many upgrades and is a fine piece of equipment, rifle started as an older 700P with a glass and aluminum bedded HS Precision stock. I upgraded to the KRG chassis to give it a little more weight and adjustability. Rifle shoots 1 MOA all day long. Bore is clean and has plenty of life, do not know the shot count but .308 barrels are generally good for around 3,500-5,000 rounds. I doubt it even close to that based on the tight groups achieved with the rifle. The action itself shows (little) pitting from the previous owners neglect but it's really not noticeable. The shot cycle is VERY manageable nothing comparable to a .308 deer rifle. The muzzlebrake makes this a sweet shooter.
I have shot multiple loads through this gun and all perform very well. Inc. hornaday whitetail classic, fusion, S&B, Remington, and hand loads. I did notice some pressure issues when shooting 200grn projectiles. Bolt got a little sticky on cycling but everything under 175gr runs flawlessly. Trigger is stock never changed it because I never thought it needed a new one. Once again this is a serious built precision rifle and anyone who wishes to own it will have no doubts. Message me for any pics or questions. Optics not included, I have a SWFA 10x scope and ringed I could throw in for the right trade/ price.

postcontent:
The skinny.  I purchased this from a Black Powder competition shooter about 4 years ago.  For two reasons.  Admit watching Clink Eastwood movies and getting pulled into the coolness of the gun, but primarily my father is a for reals 7th Cav Company Commander with a huge combat military record, and historian.  He takes his part of the 7th Cav history seriously.  So thought he would enjoy the idea of this.  The weapon essentially sat.  Turns out the weapon has been fired approximately 20 times.  Mainly by my nephew who is on the Harvard shooting team.  He gave it a big thumbs up.  

What else I know about the firearm is that coming from a competitive shooter, he had some custom work done on it.  Have the paperwork that indicates a smoothing of the bore and a couple other things.  I am hardly an expert on these weapons but I get the sense this one is sweet.  It's action is smooth.  It is definitely a solid piece and I would grade it Very Good+ condition.  It is probably better than that but this is my take.  Everything works on it.  

I also have several additions to go with it as shown in a picture.  The black powder container is 80% full.  The Hornady box is 90% full.  And the brass powder flask.  And a leather holster.  And 2 tins of caps also 90% full.  Same for the cloth wads.   I sourced all these additions and it came to approx $75-$90.  Everything is for all intents new.  

It just sits.  Hence I need to get it into capable hands.   OBO.

title: For Sale:  1860 Colt Army Percussion Revolver with Ivory Grips, .44 cal, mfg. 1867 (wild west era)
postcontent: Wild West Era M1860 Colt Army Percussion Revolver with Ivory Grips, .44 cal, mfg. 1867. This is a crisp, great looking Colt revolver featuring matching serial numbers on the frame, barrel, cylinder, backstrap, and triggerguard. The wedge is un-numbered. The gun has a gray patina overall with faint traces of original bluing under the barrel and plum traces in protected areas of the cylinder and breech. The frame and hammer have a slight hue of case color which has turned silvery/brown. There are some light traces of original Silver finish in protected areas of the triggerguard. The Ivory grips are original to the period and fit the gun well. There is some minor shrinkage along the face of the triggerguard and slight swelling along the butt. The grips have a wonderful mellow patina with various age checks and an old crack on the left front toe. Overall the edges of the gun are very sharp, and the cylinder scene is very clear. Notice the holster wear on the muzzle! This gun was certainly used but well taken care of. Serial numbers, patent stamp, caliber marking, and barrel address are all very clear. Original German Silver blade front sight. The action is tight and crisp, it functions perfectly. The nipples are all very clean originals and the bore is very good considering it's age. It has good, strong rifling front to back with light blackpowder frosting, most notably toward the muzzle. I think a good cleaning will improve it. This is just a good, handsome early Colt with a great set of grips that was no doubt used in the frontier!
